        }
    }
    Console.WriteLine(&quot;Okay. If you are in the mood for &quot; + wtd + &quot;, then you should go &quot; + act + &quot;and travel in &quot; + trav + &quot;.&quot;);

The `isTrue` variable will tell the loop to continue looping, so for instance, if the user input `1`, it&#39;ll set the variable to false, to end the loop, if the user input any numbers larger than 4, it&#39;ll just keep it inside the loop and it&#39;ll start over again. 

I&#39;ve also replaced this line `result = Convert.ToInt32(Console.ReadLine());` with this `int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out result);` you should always use TryParse instead of converting the integers directly. the `TryParse` will check the string, if is it a valid integers, then will parse it, and it&#39;ll return true (as it&#39;s an integer) and the out will be the parsed integer. if the parse failed, it&#39;ll return false. 

This way, you&#39;ll ensure you only get integers.

